{"id":14881532,"mediaExerciseId":"9efe2832-ae48-4e70-8fa9-420a1fb88ad6","exerciseName":"1","chapterName":"16","chapterTitle":"Financial Leverage and Capital Structure Policy","groupId":null,"groupTitle":null,"isPremium":true,"sectionName":"16.1","sectionTitle":"The Capital Structure Question","pageNumber":536,"solutions":[{"id":5991690,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"$a)$ The financial manager must select a capital structure that optimizes the firm's value while lowering its weighted average cost of capital. The total cost of all sources of raised capital is referred to as the weighted average cost of capital, as a consequence, financial management will concentrate on lowering the weighted average cost of capital and increasing the firm's worth.\n\n In a conclusion, financial managers select capital structures that maximize the firm's value while lowering the weighted average cost of capital.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":256,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/0cc226163d7d65e9db2903cd071d9c00/01e5601bc03b47a2cdd0160e91c3aae2/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":128,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/0cc226163d7d65e9db2903cd071d9c00/01e5601bc03b47a2cdd0160e91c3aae2/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"$b)$ There seems to be a negative link between the weighted average cost of capital and the firm's worth, as smaller the company's weighted average cost of capital, the higher its value will be, there must be two factors that contribute to a growth in a company's value. \n\nWhether the company has had tremendous growth in the past, or it has made efficient use of its resources, leading to a lower cost of capital.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":218,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/0cc226163d7d65e9db2903cd071d9c00/a5cc108feb7f4d01cf1826ed296f68b3/lateximg_large.png","width":998},"regular":{"height":110,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/0cc226163d7d65e9db2903cd071d9c00/a5cc108feb7f4d01cf1826ed296f68b3/lateximg.png","width":500}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"$c)$ Any capital structure that lowers the firm's weighted average cost of capital is ideal, to put it another way, when a firm's weighted average cost of capital is minimized as a consequence of its capital structure, that capital structure is considered to be optimal, whenever the weighted average cost of capital is as low as possible, the firm's value is increased.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":181,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/0cc226163d7d65e9db2903cd071d9c00/c3c8882718f208941b728a1f968b54b7/lateximg_large.png","width":998},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/0cc226163d7d65e9db2903cd071d9c00/c3c8882718f208941b728a1f968b54b7/lateximg.png","width":500}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"c3cd1b83-9604-40e4-bbae-cf1960f1566d","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{